description.para: All plots on landslide scars and deposits, on all aspects, slopes 50-173%, elevation 1500-3600 ft, on clearcut sites, undisturbed forest sites, roadcuts and roadfills. Landslides occured between 1953 and 1975.

samplingDescription.para: Twenty 4.5 mi-acre were plots established in a grid pattern across each lankslide surface (fewer if landslide too small to fit 20 plots). Plots are circular.

attribute.attributeDefinition: Landslide site number
Treatment- landslide(1) or clearcut (2)
Failure type: management type causing landslide
Slope gradient of landslide in degrees
Average aspect of landslide
Area affected by landslide including scar and nearby deposits
Date of slide - year of 1st occurance of landsliding
Date data collected
Elevation
Plot number on each landslide from 1 to 20
Substrate source and condition class- landslide surface feature and source of it (5 classes)

codeDefinition.definition: Angle of repose: steep section of scar through which erosional material may move, but which does not experience any major net loss or gain of material
Primary deposition: areas which recieved the original landslide debris, but do not recieve secondary accumulations of erosional material
Erosional: section of scar from which a significant net loss of substrate material occurs annually
Secondary accumulation: areas in which post-landslide erosional materials are deposited

attribute.attributeDefinition: Litter cover - ocular estimate of % litter cover
Litter depth - ocular average measured depth of litter
Vegetation cover - ocular estimate of % vegetative cover
Total height of douglas fir tree
Total age at breast height in years
Growth age - age of tree for which height growth measurement was taken
Height growth - taken for the 5 years of growth previous to the growth age
Diameter growth increment - 1st measurement on each stem
Diameter growth increment - 2nd measurement in opposite direction of 1st measurement- if assymetry present
Diameter at breast height at the end of the diameter gouwth increment
Tree density - number of trees per plot
Stockability: capability of plot to become stocked (artificially or naturally)

codeDefinition.definition: Marginally stockable: plot unstocked, w/ potential for natural or artificial establishement, but seedling would have poor chance for survival under standard management practices
Unstockable plot: unstocked, with natural or artificial seedling establishment & survival unlikely under standard management practices
Stocked: plot contained at least 1 established individual seedling of a potentially commercial conifer species
Stockable: plot unstocked, but a commercial conifer species seedling could become established naturally, or be established artificially.
